// bigint.su — arbitrary-precision integer arithmetic helpers.
//
// Per planning/sutra-spec/arbitrary-precision.md (Option A, all four
// sub-decisions locked Emma 2026-05-28). Ergonomic wrappers over the
// substrate intrinsics int_div, int_mod, and digit_array_add (declared
// in logic.su § "Section 3 — intrinsic declarations").
//
// Representation: a BigInt value is a 1-d substrate vector of `max_digits`
// elements, each holding a base-10 digit in [0, 9]. Little-endian:
// digit[0] is the ones place, digit[1] is the tens, ..., digit[N-1] is
// the most-significant place. Overflow saturates by dropping the top
// carry-out (matching the String overflow posture per strings.md).
//
// The wider `BigInt<MAX>` const-templated form (sub-decision 1) keeps
// MAX in the declared type but at the runtime is just a digit-array
// vector of length MAX. The class declaration below ships the
// type-name wrapper + the `+` operator overload; user code can now
// write `BigInt a = ...; BigInt b = ...; BigInt c = a + b;` and the
// `+` lowers to `bigint_add` via method-operator dispatch (same
// pattern as `String.string_concat` in strings.su).
//
// Worked example end-to-end: experiments/bigint_worked_example.py
// demonstrates `bigint_add` on the spec's `"99999" + "1" = "100000"`
// case + 8 other cases including cascade and overflow-saturates.


// bigint_add — add two digit-array BigInt values.
//
// Inputs: 1-d vectors `a` and `b` of equal length N, each digit in
// [0, 10). Returns: 1-d vector of length N with the carry-propagated
// sum digits; the top-digit carry-out is silently dropped (overflow
// saturates at N digits). Substrate-pure end-to-end — the digit array
// never round-trips through host scalars; carry propagation is the
// `digit_array_add` substrate intrinsic.
function vector bigint_add(vector a, vector b) {
    return digit_array_add(a, b, 10);
}


// BigInt class — type-name wrapper for digit-array BigInt values.
//
// Per planning/sutra-spec/arbitrary-precision.md sub-decision 1
// (BigInt class form) — extends vector, holds the same digit-array
// substrate representation as the bare-function form above. The class
// declaration is a typing refinement: code that takes/returns BigInt
// gets the BigInt static type, but the runtime representation is the
// same digit-array 1-d vector.
//
// The `operator +` overload (below) lets user code write
// `BigInt a = ...; BigInt b = ...; BigInt c = a + b;`. It dispatches via
// the same mechanism as `String`'s `operator +` -> `string_concat`: a
// plain (non-intrinsic) operator method whose body calls a FREE
// intrinsic. The codegen lowers `return digit_array_add(a, b, 10)` to
// `return _VSA.digit_array_add(a, b, 10)` (see codegen_base
// `_emit_stdlib_class_operators`). Because the operator body calls the
// free `digit_array_add` directly — rather than re-declaring it as a
// static intrinsic method on BigInt — the free `digit_array_add` and the
// `bigint_add` wrapper both stay intact, and the stdlib loader's
// duplicate-name rule is never triggered. (The earlier f34103b2 deferral
// assumed the only path was re-declaring the intrinsic on the class; the
// operator-calls-free-intrinsic path needs no intrinsic-registry change.)
//
// Construction helpers (from string literal, from int, from string
// codepoint extraction) are still deferred — users build a BigInt by
// packing a digit-array vector for now.
//
// Radix is fixed to 10 per arbitrary-precision.md sub-decision 2.
class BigInt extends vector {
    method operator +(BigInt a, BigInt b) {
        return digit_array_add(a, b, 10);
    }
}
